nd conflict-affected contexts -- tBeyond extraction: co-creating a decolonial and feminist research practice in post-conflict Guatemala -- tConclusion -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCrises such as the COVID-19 pandemic, disasters, or violent conflict present numerous challenges for researchers. Faced with disruption, obstacles, and even danger to their own lives, researchers in times of crisis must adapt or redesign existing research methods in order to continue their work effectively. Including contributions on qualitative and digital research from Europe, Asia, Africa, Australasia, and the Americas, this volume explores the creative and thoughtful ways in which researchers have adapted methods and rethought relationships in response to challenges arising from crises. Their collective reflections, strategies, and practices highlight the importance of responsive, ethical, and creative research design and the need to develop methods for fostering mutual, reflexive, and healthy relationships in times of crisis.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aQualitative research. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Methodology.2bisacsh1 aBaldassar, Loretta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBasu, Anirban, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBowen-Salter, Holly, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDahal, Bibek, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDarbyshire, Tessa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDwyer, Natasha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEvans, Bettina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFitzGibbon, Ali, econtributor.4ctb4